G.f.: g(x) = (Sum_{k > 0} c(k)*x^k)/(1-x), where c(k) = Sum_{j > 1, j|k} (floor(log_2(j)) - floor(log_2(j - 1))).

lim sup (n - log_2(n) - a(n)) = 0, for n-->oo.
lim sup (a(n + 1) - a(n) - log_2(n)) = 0, for n-->oo. (End)

A011540.name: Numbers that contain a digit 0.
formula: Set m := floor(log_10(n)) + 1), j := floor(sign(n+1 - (8*10^m - 9*9^m + 17)/8) + 1)/2) + m - 1, d := 10^j - 9^j, b := (8*10^j - 9*9^j + 17)/8, and determine r(n) as follows:
Case 1: r(n) = a(b - d + (n - b) mod d), if (n - b) mod d > 10^(j-1) and n >= 19
Case 2: r(n) = (n - b) mod d, if (n - b) mod d <= 10^(j-1).
Set m := floor(log_10(n)) + 1), j := floor((sign(n+1 - (8*10^m - 9*9^m + 17)/8) + 1)/2) + m - 1, and determine k and c(i) as follows:
c(1) = n - (8*10^j - 9*9^j + 17)/8, then define successively for i = 1, 2, ...,
c(i+1) = (c(i) mod (10^(j-i+1) - 9^(j-i+1))) - 10^(j-i) while this value is > 0, and set k := i for the last such index for which c(i) > 0 (in any case k is k<=j).
g(x) = Sum_{k >= 1} g_k(x), where the terms g_k(x) obey the following recurrence relation:
A summation term g_k(x) of the g.f. represents all the sequence terms >= 10^k and < 10^(k+1).
Example 1: g_1(x) = 10*x^2*(1 - 10x^9 + 9x^10)/(1-x)^2 represents the g.f. fragment 10x^2 + 20x^3 + ... + 90x^10 and so generates the terms a(2)=10 ... a(10)=90.

The number C(n) of zero-containing numbers <= n (counting function) is given by C(n) = A011540_inverse(n), if n is a zero-containing number, and C(n) = A011540_inverse(A052382(a(n) + 1 - n)), if n is a zerofree number.

A011784.name: Levine's sequence. First construct a triangle as follows. Row 1 is {1,1}; if row n is {r_1, ..., r_k} then row n+1 consists of {r_k 1's, r_{k-1} 2's, r_{k-2} 3's, etc.}; sequence consists of the final elements in each row.
formula: Additional remarks: The sequence is generated by this array, the final term in each row forming the sequence:
where we start with the first row {1 1} and produce the rest of the array recursively as follows:
Suppose line n is {a_1, ..., a_k}; then line n+1 contains a_k 1's, a_{k-1} 2's, etc.
So the fifth line contains three 1's, two 2's, one 3 and one 4.
where the n-th term a(n) is the sum of the elements in row n-2
= the number of elements in row n-1
= the last element in row n
= the number of 1's in row n+1
If the n-th row is r_{n,i} then
Let {a( )} be the sequence; s(i,j) = j-th partial sum of the i-th row,
L(i) is the length of that row and S(i) = its sum. Then
Eric Rains and Bjorn Poonen have shown (June 1997) that the log of the n-th term is asymptotic to constant times phi^n, where phi = golden number.
This follows from the inequalities S(n) <= a(n)L(n) and S(n+1) >= ([L(n+1)/a(n)]+1) choose 2)*a(n).
The n-th term is approximately exp(a*phi^n)/I, where phi = golden number, a = .05427 (last digit perhaps 6 or 8), I = .277 (last digit perhaps 6 or 8) (Colin Mallows).

A011847.name: Triangle of numbers read by rows: T(n,k) = floor( C(n,k)/(k+1) ), where k=0..n-1 and n >= 1.
formula: The rows are palindromic: T(n, k) = T(n, n-k-1) for n >= 1 and 0 <= k <= n-1.

A011848.name: a(n) = floor(binomial(n,2)/2).
formula: a(n) = A054925(n) - A133872(n+2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 09 2014
Euler transform of length 4 sequence [ 3, -1, 0, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Nov 18 2016

A011858.name: a(n) = floor( n*(n-1)/5 ).
formula: Euler transform of length 5 sequence [2, 1, 0, -1, 1]. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 04 2011
a(1-n) = a(n). a(n) = a(n-5) + 2*n - 6 for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 04 2011
a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-5) - a(n-6) + 2 for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 06 2011
a(n) - 2*a(n+1) + a(n+2) = (n == 1 (mod 5)) + (n == 3 (mod 5)) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 19 2014

A011859.name: Normalized sequence of cumulants formed from moments in a quantum many-body problem at its critical point.
formula: a(n) = (-4)^n / (2 * Pi) * Integral_{x=-oo..oo} sech(x) * tanh^n(x) * (d^(n-1) / dx^(n-1)) tanh(x) dx. [Corrected and improved by _Sean A. Irvine_, Jul 02 2018]

A011863.name: Nearest integer to (n/2)^4.
formula: a(n) = n^4/16 - 1/32 + (-1)^n/32 - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 07 2010, adapted to added a(0) by _Hugo Pfoertner_, Dec 29 2019
a(n) = (2*A000583(n) + (-1)^n - 1)/32. - _Bruno Berselli_, Dec 07 2010, adapted to added a(0) by _Hugo Pfoertner_, Dec 29 2019
n*(n^2+n+2)*a(n+1) = 4*(n^2+2*n+2)*a(n)+(n+2)*(n^2+3*n+4)*a(n-1). Holonomic Ansatz with smallest order of recurrence. - _Thotsaporn Thanatipanonda_, Dec 12 2010
a(n) = floor(n^4/8)/2. - _Gary Detlefs_, Feb 19 2011, adapted to added a(0) by _Hugo Pfoertner_, Dec 29 2019
a(n) = A212714(n)/2, n >= 0. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Oct 03 2016, adapted to added a(0) by _Hugo Pfoertner_, Dec 29 2019

A011871.name: [ n(n-1)/18 ].
formula: a(n) = floor( (1/3) * sum_{i=1..n} floor(i/3) ). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 06 2014

A011886.name: a(n) = floor(n*(n-1)*(n-2)/4).
formula: f(n) = floor(Sum_{k=0..n} n*(k+1)/2) for n >= -2. - _William A. Tedeschi_, Sep 10 2010

A011891.name: a(n) = floor( n*(n-1)*(n-2)/9 ).
formula: Third differences are [-2, 4] repeated. - _M. F. Hasler_, Sep 15 2009

A011900.name: a(n) = 6*a(n-1) - a(n-2) - 2 with a(0) = 1, a(1) = 3.
formula: Sqrt(2) = Sum_{n>=0} 1/a(n); a(n) = a(n-1) + floor(1/(sqrt(2) - Sum_{k=0..n-1} 1/a(k))) (n>0) with a(0)=1. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Jan 25 2004
a(n+1) = a(n) * (a(n) + 2) / a(n-1) for n>=1 with a(0)=1. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Apr 08 2012
a(n) = a(-1-n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 23 2019

A011906.name: If b(n) is A011900(n) and c(n) is A001109(n), then a(n) = b(n)*c(n) = b(n) + (b(n)+1) + (b(n)+2) + ... + c(n).
formula: Lim_{n -> infinity} a(n)/a(n-1) = A156164. - _César Aguilera_, Jul 17 2020

A011922.name: a(n) = 15*a(n-1) - 15*a(n-2) + a(n-3).
formula: a(n) = A001075(n)^2 - A001353(n)^2. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Aug 24 2013

A011934.name: a(n) = |1^3 - 2^3 + 3^3 - 4^3 + ... + (-1)^(n+1)*n^3|.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} floor((2*n+1)*k/2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Apr 01 2017

A011943.name: Numbers n such that any group of n consecutive integers has integral standard deviation {viz. A011944(n)}.
formula: a(n) = T(n, 7) = (S(n, 14)-S(n-2, 14))/2 = T(2*n, 2) with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2) and T(n, x), resp. U(n, x), are Chebyshev's polynomials of the first, resp. second, kind. See A053120 and A049310. S(-2, x) := -1, S(-1, x) := 0, S(n, 14)=A007655(n+2).

A011944.name: a(n) = 14*a(n-1) - a(n-2) with a(0) = 0, a(1) = 2.
formula: For all members x of the sequence, 12*x^2 +1 is a square. Lim_{n->infinity} a(n)/a(n-1) = 7 + sqrt(12). - _Gregory V. Richardson_, Oct 13 2002

A011945.name: Areas of almost-equilateral Heronian triangles (integral side lengths m-1, m, m+1 and integral area).
formula: s(n) = floor((a+1)/4)*sqrt(3*(a+3)*(a-1)), where a=A016064(n). - _Zak Seidov_, Feb 23 2005
a(n) = (s/4)*( (7 + 4*s)^n - (7 - 4*s)^n ), where s = sqrt(3). - _Zak Seidov_, Apr 02 2014

A011965.name: Second differences of Bell numbers.
formula: a(n) = A000110(n) - 2*A000110(n-1) + A000110(n-2). - Andrey Goder (andy.goder(AT)gmail.com), Dec 17 2007

G.f.: G(0) where G(k) = 1 - 2*x*(k+1)/((2*k+1)*(2*x*k+2*x-1) - x*(2*k+1)*(2*k+3)*(2*x*k+2*x-1)/(x*(2*k+3) - 2*(k+1)*(2*x*k+3*x-1)/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 19 2012
G.f.: 1 - G(0) where G(k) = 1 - 1/(1-k*x-2*x)/(1-x/(x-1/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 17 2013
G.f.: 1 - 1/x + (1-x)^2/x/(G(0)-x) where G(k) =  1 - x*(k+1)/(1 - x/G(k+1) ); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 26 2013
G.f.: G(0)*(1-1/x) where G(k) =  1 - 1/(1-x*(k+1))/(1-x/(x-1/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Feb 07 2013

A011966.name: Third differences of Bell numbers.
formula: G.f.: -(1-x+x^2)/x^2 + (1-x)^3/x^2/(G(0)-x) where G(k) =  1 - x*(k+1)/(1 - x/G(k+1) ); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 26 2013

A011968.name: Apply (1+Shift) to Bell numbers.
formula: For n >= 1, a(n+1) = exp(-1)*Sum_{k>=0} ((k+1)/k!)*k^n. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 09 2008
For n >= 1, a(n) = Bell(n) + Bell(n-1). - _Augustine O. Munagi_, Jul 17 2008

G.f.: G(0) where G(k) = 1 - 2*x*(k+1)/((2*k+1)*(2*x*k-1) - x*(2*k+1)*(2*k+3)*(2*x*k-1)/(x*(2*k+3) - 2*(k+1)*(2*x*k+x-1)/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 19 2012
G.f.: 1 + x*E(0) where E(k) = 1 + 1/(1-x*k-x)/(1-x/(x+1/E(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 20 2013

A011969.name: Apply (1+Shift)^2 to Bell numbers.
formula: For n>=1, a(n+2)= exp(-1)*sum(k>=0,(k+1)^2/k!*k^n). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Mar 09 2008
If n>1, then a(n)=Bell(n)+2*Bell(n-1)+Bell(n-2). - _Augustine O. Munagi_, Jul 17 2008

G.f.: G(0)*(1+x) where G(k) = 1 - 2*x*(k+1)/((2*k+1)*(2*x*k-1) - x*(2*k+1)*(2*k+3)*(2*x*k-1)/(x*(2*k+3) - 2*(k+1)*(2*x*k+x-1)/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jan 03 2013.

A011970.name: Apply (1+Shift)^3 to Bell numbers.
formula: If n>2, then bell(n)+3*bell(n-1)+3*bell(n-2)+bell(n-3). - _Augustine O. Munagi_, Jul 17 2008

A011971.name: Aitken's array: triangle of numbers {a(n,k), n >= 0, 0 <= k <= n} read by rows, defined by a(0,0)=1, a(n,0) = a(n-1,n-1), a(n,k) = a(n,k-1) + a(n-1,k-1).
formula: Double-exponential generating function: Sum_{n, k} a(n-k, k) x^n y^k / n! k! = exp(e^{x+y}-1+x). - _Don Knuth_, Sep 21 2002 [U coordinates, reversed]

A011972.name: Sequence formed by reading rows of triangle defined in A011971.

A011973.name: Triangle of numbers {binomial(n-k, k), n >= 0, 0 <= k <= floor(n/2)}; or, triangle of coefficients of (one version of) Fibonacci polynomials.
formula: Let F(n, x) be the n-th Fibonacci polynomial in x; the g.f. for F(n, x) is Sum_{n>=0} F(n, x)*y^n = (1 + x*y)/(1 - y - x*y^2). - _Paul D. Hanna_

T(m, n) = 0 for n != 0 and m <= 1 T(0, 0) = T(1, 0) = 1 T(m, n) = T(m - 1, n) + T(m-2, n-1) for m >= 2 (i.e., like the recurrence for Pascal's triangle A007318, but going up one row as well as left one column for the second summand). E.g., T(7, 2) = 10 = T(6, 2) + T(5, 1) = 6 + 4. - _Rob Arthan_, Sep 22 2003
Identities for the Fibonacci polynomials F(n, x):
The degree of F(n, x) is floor((n-1)/2) and F(2p, x) = F(p, x) times a polynomial of equal degree which is 1 mod p.
G.f.: 1/(1-x-y*x^2) = R(0)/2, where R(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - (2*k+1+ x*y)*x/((2*k+2+ x*y)*x + 1/R(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 09 2013

O.g.f. G(x,t) = x/(1-x-tx^2) = x + x^2 + (1+t) x^3 + (1+2t) x^4 + ... has the inverse Ginv(x,t) = -[1+x-sqrt[(1+x)^2 + 4tx^2]]/(2tx) = x - x^2  + (1-t) x^3 + (-1+3t) x^4 + ... , an o.g.f. for the signed Motzkin polynomials of A055151, consistent with A134264 with h_0 = 1, h_1 = -1, h_2 = -t, and h_n = 0 otherwise. - _Tom Copeland_, Jan 21 2016

O.g.f. H(x,t) = x (1+tx)/ [1-x(1+tx)] = x + (1+t) x^2 + (1+2t) x^3 + ... = -L[Cinv(-tx)/t], where L(x) = x/(1+x) with inverse Linv(x) = x/(1-x) and Cinv(x) = x (1-x) is the inverse of C(x) = (1-sqrt(1-4x))/2, the o.g.f. of the shifted Catalan numbers A000108. Then Hinv(x,t) = -C[t Linv(-x)]/t = [-1 + sqrt(1+4tx/(1+x))]/2t = x - (1+t) x^2 + (1+2t+2t^2) x^3 - (1+3t+6t^2+5t^3) x^4 + ... , which is signed A098474, reverse of A124644. - _Tom Copeland_, Jan 25 2016

A011974.name: 2 followed by the numbers that are the sum of 2 successive primes.

A011997.name: Number of (n,3,7) difference families over Z_n.

A012000.name: Expansion of 1/sqrt(1 - 4*x + 16*x^2).
formula: Scaled Legendre polynomials evaluated at 1/2: 2^(2n)P(n, 1/2). - _Michael Somos_, Dec 03, 2001
D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) +2*(1-2*n)*a(n-1) +16*(n-1)*a(n-2)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 14 2011
G.f.: G(0), where G(k)= 1 + x*(1-x)*(4*k+1)/( 4*k+2 - x*(1-x)*(4*k+2)*(4*k+3)/(x*(1-x)*(4*k+3) + 4*(k+1)/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Jul 06 2013
